<div id="review_1998791439" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1998791439" />
    <a title="Christian D.  Orr" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16857218-christian-d-orr"><img alt="Christian D.  Orr" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1359302419p2/16857218.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1998791439?book_show_action=true">Jun 12, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Christian D.  Orr" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Christian D.  Orr" href="/user/show/16857218-christian-d-orr">Christian D.  Orr</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Sci-fi fans</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1998791439" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10581860122762251867">One of the classic TEOTWAWKI (&quot;The End of the World As We Know It&quot;) novels about a comet striking the Earth, published in 1977 and thus predating films like &quot;Armageddon&quot; and &quot;Deep Impact&quot; by a good solid decade.<br/><br/>A gripping, scientifically well-grounded, frighteningly realistic storyline and a diverse cast of characters that hold the reader&apos;s interest. And as someone who grew up in L.A, the SoCal locations--particularly the San Fernando Valley--make the novel relatable for me at a personal level; </span>
  <span id="freeText10581860122762251867" style="display:none">One of the classic TEOTWAWKI ("The End of the World As We Know It") novels about a comet striking the Earth, published in 1977 and thus predating films like "Armageddon" and "Deep Impact" by a good solid decade.<br /><br />A gripping, scientifically well-grounded, frighteningly realistic storyline and a diverse cast of characters that hold the reader's interest. And as someone who grew up in L.A, the SoCal locations--particularly the San Fernando Valley--make the novel relatable for me at a personal level; it was first recommended to me back in 1985 by two real-life Jet Propulsion Lab (JPL) employees....and JPL factors prominently in the plot.<br /><br />RANDOM STREAM OF CONSCIOUSNESS NOTES AND OBSERVATIONS:<br /><br />--p. 33: "There was this about the morning rush hour: The freeways were jammed, but not necessarily with idiots....Despite the stand-up comics who had made California drivers the joke of the world, they were much better on freeways than any people she had seen elsewhere" Can't say I disagree with that assessment.<br /><br />--p. 69: "People who got on 'The Tonight Show' were important." As Ed McMahon used to say to Johnny Carson (may they both RIP), "YES, HAW HAW HAW!! You are correct, sir!"<br /><br />--p. 78: Halley's Comet and BROOKS' Comet!! 😮<br /><br />--p. 87: Mayor Bentley Allen = Tom Bradley?<br /><br />--p. 108: "He drank at stiff attention. It was one way of showing disapproval of officers who drank before lunch." Eh, get the stick out of your arse, Sergeant Breslov of the Red Army!<br /><br />--p. 149: "'You don't tease your Russian counterpart about his name. Resist the temptation.'" Pieter Jakov, too damn funny! (But shouldn't that be Piotr?) <br /><br />--p. 156: "Space is not cold." Really? I was taught differently as a kid.<br />"A man generates more heat inside each cubic inch of his body than the Sun does in each cubic inch of its surface."<br /><br />--p. 158: "Saki" [sic] Shouldn't that be "sake?"<br /><br />--p. 159: Lilith, a stripper with a "heart-shaped face;" compare to S.A. Bailey's stripper Khandi with the heart-shaped ass!<br /><br />--p. 165: SAC-trained killer, hooah!<br /><br />--p. 166: Gen. Thomas Bambridge of SAC modelled after Curtis E. LeMay?<br /><br />--p. 176: Wow, the pre-PC days when people still said "Oriental" instead of "Asian!" Is Johnny Kim modelled after Mike Woo?<br /><br />--p. 210: Ah, back in the day when "gay" still meant "happy."<br /><br />--p. 240: Air Force cops didn't carry submachine guns back then (and nor do they now), they carried M-16 rifles.<br /><br />--p. 283: WIKIPEDIA LOOKUP Hottentots<br /><br />--p. 340: Marty Robbins, like the singer?<br /><br />--p: 459: "Army submachine guns?" Ahem, that should be Army *rifles*.<br /><br />--p. 497: Haha, a "Monty Python's Flying Circus" reference!<br /><br />CENTRAL CASTING: James Franco as Brig. Gen. Johnny Baker, Will Smith as Lt.<br />Col. Rick Delanty, Jude Law as Brigadier Pieter, Rachel Wiesz as Leonilla Alexandrovna Malik, Hal Fishman (if he were still alive, R.I.P.) as Harvey Randall, Silent Bob or Zach Gallifinakis(sp?) as Mark Czesku or Harry the postman, Chris Cooper as Sen. Jellison, Kirsten Dunst or Laura Prepon as Maureen Jellison<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="10581860122762251867" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


