<div id="review_2795479331" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2795479331" />
    <a title="Austin Prince" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7005820-austin-prince"><img alt="Austin Prince" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2795479331?book_show_action=true">Apr 22, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Austin Prince" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Austin Prince" href="/user/show/7005820-austin-prince">Austin Prince</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2795479331" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14767869993437541250">TLDR: the dialogue is great, the set-up was good, the apocalypse was fun, and the ending was hopeful, but this book&apos;s regressive social opinions do not stand the test of time.<br/><br/>The allure of the post-apocalyptic genre does not arise solely from morbid curiosity, conservatism, or Michael Bay explosions. The characters even mention it in the beginning - it is the desire for personal meaning in your life. A society-ender shatters alienation. You may safely pause from keeping up with the Facebook Jone</span>
  <span id="freeText14767869993437541250" style="display:none">TLDR: the dialogue is great, the set-up was good, the apocalypse was fun, and the ending was hopeful, but this book's regressive social opinions do not stand the test of time.<br /><br />The allure of the post-apocalyptic genre does not arise solely from morbid curiosity, conservatism, or Michael Bay explosions. The characters even mention it in the beginning - it is the desire for personal meaning in your life. A society-ender shatters alienation. You may safely pause from keeping up with the Facebook Joneses, from workplace kaizen, from commutes, and from all the other soul traps the lawyers, accountants, and tech paradigm shifters have constructed for us. If life is Sisyphean anyway, then a world ender enables us to roll only the boulders that truly matter. It is enforced mindfulness, without the subscription service offer or preaching that always accompanies these messages. <br /><br />After the end of the world, you can rebuild it in the way of your choosing. And the way the authors' chose to build, destroy, and rebuild this world were fascinating in some respects and hopelessly regressive in others. <br /><br />The dialogue in the beginning was fantastic, being engaging enough to transport you to the dinner parties and boardrooms muddied only by irony's growing eclipse. The disaster itself was spectacular: plausible yet terrifying. The side story of the astronauts is almost a microcosm for what unfolds down on Earth. The civilization they attempt to build is interesting as well. <br /><br />The two major problems I have with this story (-1 star for each) are: 1. the story does not benefit from 70's-era sociology and 2. the war scene seemed too advanced and well-armed for a society so recently destroyed. <br /><br />I want to enunciate point number 1 a little more. Racism and sexism are abound in this book. As in most media from this era, every character is physically described only in as much as they do not resemble Superman. The default option for every character is strong, big, male, and Caucasian. Only deviations from this ideal are mentioned and, in many cases, these deviations serve as their sole characterizations. <br /><br />The only black characters are either criminals, government employees (leeches in the subtext of this novel), cannibalistic slaves (seriously!), or one astronaut who only got chosen for the space mission because of affirmative action. All women are described based on their attractiveness and none are allowed any agency or moments of genius without it being approved of or qualified by male characters. Granted, some of them are rocks of stability when their male mate falters, but even then they serve only to reorient men away from despair. The one exception might be the Russian MD astronaut, but even she is relegated to a masculine other after initial comments are made about her physical appearance. Pretty sure it fails the Bechdel test, too. <br /><br />My hope was that these characterizations were set-ups. They would be further evidence of a society gone wrong, that this would all disappear once the comet reminded everyone what truly mattered. This is what kept me going through to the end. But no, none of that ever resolved. In fact, it got worse as the story ended. One might argue that if tribalism could exist in our comfortable modernity, it would only be amplified after society's end. That is a fair, if depressing, point and would've been interesting (as all ideas expressed in sci-fi should be). But the social subtexts here could not have been plot devices because they were neither resolved nor explored. They were simply products of the authors' attitudes. And there is nothing futuristic about "ample wom[e]n" or Ebonics-talking thieves who also happen to be Muslim who also happen to be Black Panthers who also happen to become cannibals who also happen to become slaves at the end. </span>
  <a data-text-id="14767869993437541250" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

